  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Ammianus Marcellinus, We know the life of the historian A. 
    (c. AD 330-400) almost exclusively from his work. Its contemporary second half gave him the opportunity 
    to blend his own experiences into imperial history. A born Greek, as he says in his biographical conclusion 
    (31,16,9), he served as protector domesticus under the army commander Ursicinus, who in 355 received
    the assignment to remove the usurper Silvanus in Cologne..... The title Res gestae is found in 
    the grammarian Priscianus, the only author who cites the historian in antiquity. In the conclusion
    (31,16,9) A. explains the scope of his work: from the principate of the emperor Nerva until the downfall 
    of the emperor Valens (AD 96-378). Tacitus had continued his histories up through Nerva. A. aspires to
    continue Tacitus' work of 30 books of annals and histories and to surpass him by one book with 31 books.
    A. also follows his predecessor by connecting imperial history and imperial biography. The accident of 
    transmission took care of a further parallel: 13 of A.'s books were lost, and the loss is about as great
    for Tacitus..." Rosen, Klaus (Bonn). "Ammianus Marcellinus." Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2009. Brill Online.</mads:note>
